metadata.name: RAUSCH #26
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023 

___________________________________________________
RAUSCH Controls:

Animation: 
• ‘1 - 2 - 3 - 4’ animate views
• 'MouseClick' pause/play animation

Functions:
(press key & wait)
• 'F' 24 FPS
• 'B' b/w mode 

Resize Canvas:
(press key & wait)
• '6' Portrait A4 - 1000x1414
• '7' Landscape 16:9 - 1920x1080
• '8' Portrait 9:16 - 1080x1920
• '9' Square 1:1 - 1024x1024
• 'DoubleClick' Fullscreen

Save & Export Image:
• 'S' save a .png of in current resolution

Save & Export GIF:
• 'G' save a 1-2 sec. seamless loop .gif of current view 
• 'P' save a 12-24 sec. seamless loop .gif of all the views
• 'T’ scale down current resolution, save a 12 sec. seamless loop .gif

Steps to save a gif/png :
• go in live/open mode (wait)
• resize canvas with 6,7,8, or 9 to your desired aspect ratio (wait)
• press S,G or P to save & download (wait) 
• enjoy RAUSCH :)

Save & Export GIF for social media sharing:
• go in live/open mode (wait)
• press T or G wait for recalculation & download. 
• enjoy RAUSCH 
• post on Twitter ;)
__________________________________________________

This token may not work on mobile(!), but it allows exporting .png and .gif (see controls) to enjoy RAUSCH on different displays or mobile. Tested on Mozilla, Chrome, Safari. Created with P5js & p5.createLoop

RAUSCH Generative Token by @grasser_alex 2023

metadata.name: Badgirs City #236
metadata.description:
"I used to live in a small city placed at the center of Iran's plateau with the warmest summer days in the country part; spending most of my childhood with my sweet grandma at her old house. She was always keeping her eyes on me not to get heat stroke at noon playing in the yard when the sun was at its peak glowing furiously. Sundays at noon were my favorite, I used to call them “Ice cream” noons sitting beside the nicest person you could imagine and enjoying a delightful ice cream. You won't know how lovely it was to have an ice cream relaxing under the most enjoyable cold breeze of the tallest windcatcher in the city at her house. "



The Badgirs city is the first collaboration between Fleep and IceRain on Fxhash. The concept was established first with the design of a school with a feeling of safe and nostalgia reminding us of the good memories of our childhood as the grandma’s house and the windcatcher for Fleep.
A windcatcher (Badgir) is an Iranian traditional architectural element in the form of a small tower built on the roof of houses in warm locations to create passive cooling. The collection of Badgirs city is a modern recreational development of those traditional windcatchers designed by Fleep and icerain and exquisitely translated into code by Icerain.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: Elasticity #140
metadata.description:
Elasticity is a collection that explores the ambiguity of discrete continuity in architecture.

Elasticity is a tectonic, generative system that combines simple, discrete parts into an elastic relationship between part and whole, creating a discrete and continuous elastic form. A form that celebrates the continuity of digital variation while respecting a discrete approach to a digital whole.

It is a generative follow-up to the project CM.CollabWood, where the same parts were embedded in a real-time participatory architectural environment, where clusters of parts were placed by participants in real-time in collective design sessions to create tangible collective open forms.

___________________________________________________
Controls:
• 'P' pause/play animation
• 'B' monochrome mode (wait a bit for recalculation)

Resize Canvas in live/open mode:
(press once and wait for recalculation!)
• 'DoubleClick' go Fullscreen
• '1' square 1024x1024
• '2' square 2048x2048
• '3' square 3072x3072
• '4' square 4096x4096 (might not work on all laptops)
• '5' landscape 4000x3000
• '6' portrait 3000x4000
• '7' fullHD 1920x1080
• '8' UHD 3840 x 2160
• '9' square small(for sharing a gif on twitter) 512x512
• '0' flex. adapt to current window size

Save & Export in live/open mode:
• 's' save a .png of in current resolution
• 'g' save a seamless loop .gif in current resolution
(press the key and wait for export, might take some time, consider with higher resolutions files get pretty big)

• press s or g and wait for recalculation & download to finish
• enjoy elasticity :)

metadata.name: Lost Memories #326
metadata.description:
||_\\_//_\\_||

Let’s start with a riddle…
I’m a type of creature that never tires.
My desire to learn is truly inspired.
I’d back expanding to the letter.
As more of everything is better.
I could not stop though the world is sick.
And now my only memories are apocalyptic. 
What am I?

If you’d like to know a bit about the ideas behind this piece, and my method for a code based paint effect, see the fxtext article “Lost Memories - Painting like an impressionist android”. Link at the bottom. However feel free to skip the article, my meaning, and everything else if so desired.

||_\\_//_\\_||

Basic info:
This piece uses web tech and WebGL in experimental ways to achieve the paint-like effect. This includes a custom built drawing pipeline. Although well tested, please be sure it's fine for your devices before buying ( give it a whirl drawing basically ). 

A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that’s present.

The piece comes in portrait to make use of the depth of the body of water. The ratio is 1.5. So the initial render will be 1000px wide and 1500px high. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

||_\\_//_\\_||

Saving the image / prints
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. You will know when the render is finished as there will be 3 layers of fish made. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right-click save otherwise.

Correct sizing for HD digital images / laptops / phones
Use the [s] key (see above), at most use the [2] key ( see below ) to get double the size. Honestly, anything larger and you will begin to lose the textures as the detail becomes too fine. 

Correct sizing for large prints
I strongly suggest using the [3] key ( see below - 3000 x 4500 pixels ) for large prints. I’ve tested this on a 20x30 inch print and it’s the best size. Anything bigger will begin to lose texture and lose detail. However, the option for bigger is there. 

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x3000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x13500 size image etc ( see above for correct sizing ). After the image will be automatically downloaded.

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however.

||_\\_//_\\_||

Made with javascript (webgl) and some small extra code:
Some bits by @nathansonic
Twgl - A webgl wrapper -  twgljs.org
A Perlin noise generator - github.com/josephg/noisejs

metadata.name: Lands of Solitude #62
metadata.description:
In times of chaos and uncertainty while the digital world falls appart, some will decide to resist and build. In their blind quest for curiosity, knowledge and creation, they will endure the darkest times and as waves of departures will follow one another, very few will remain. These are the lands of solitude that await.

Controls :
* Drag and pan to rotate and zoom.
* Press « F » to toggle the All-Over mode.
* Press « G » to toggle the grid.
* Press « H » to toggle the in-world infos.
* Press the space bar to toggle the auto scroll mode.
* Press « R » to restart.

———————

Lands of Solitude by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: The Gap #75
metadata.description:
The Gap is an impressive generative art collection that showcases nature in its purest and most elemental form. At the center of the piece is a break between two walls of ice.
 The break appears to have been created by relentless ice pressure, and its shape and size are a result of the complex interaction between water, ice, and underlying geology.
But what truly captures the viewer's attention are the brilliant colors surrounding the break. The sky is depicted in a warm, brilliant color, while the break is depicted in a cold, brilliant color. These flat, saturated colors create a striking contrast that makes the break stand out in the landscape. Together, these colors create a vibrant and evocative atmosphere that invites viewers to dive into the landscape and explore its details.
In summary, The Gap is a unique work that combines technology and nature to create a stunning and impactful visual experience. With its contrast of warm and cold, brilliant flat colors, this work is a statement about the strength and simplicity of nature, and a call to action to protect our planet.

metadata.name: Morpheus #161
metadata.description:
A spinning, shapeshifting Morpheus which constantly changes form. 

3 Different Rotation types: 
Normal - 55% chance
Enhanced - 25% chance
Max - 20% chance

18 Palettes: 
15 with a 6% chance to appear
2 rare (Reds 4%, Greens 4%) 
1 very rare (Mono 2%)

Mouse click - or tap screen change all of the background colors

Some key functions: 
s - save output as png 
r - change from the standard rotation to a random different rotation amount
1 - randomly change the background color for the top left
2 - randomly change the background color for the top right	
3 - randomly change the background color for the bottom left
4 - randomly change the background color for the bottom right
c - Change the border and stroke colors of the Morpheus

Made in p5.js
P1xelboy 
May 2022

metadata.name: Flume #55
metadata.description:
Flume are infinitely flowing digital bodies of water.
The flow of Flumes can range from slow and gentle, creating small ripples and eddies, to fast and turbulent, carving its way through the inner workings of your computer screen. 
The color, clarity, and viscosity of the water can also vary.

This is the culmination of my collection Flume, an exploration into On-Chain art on Ethereum, https://etherscan.io/address/0x1fa23513825f952afca07a603ac3f312ebee4ca9

These pieces were all created in p5js.

- Andrew

metadata.name: Automatic #393
metadata.description:
Cellular automata is fascinating :) Applications ranging from physics and biology to modeling and architecture, with artistic and aesthetic representation always following along. Perfect example for emergence, how simple even byte-size rules result in complex structures, forming patterns and unpredictable behaviors...

This one is simple, 1d elementary cellular automata and the 256 rules as the foundation, where each iteration consists of the following elements: base rules - 3 are selected and allocated into the start row compositions, a set of shapes is assigned to a grid of various sizes. Occasionally, dynamic rule set is added - where a rule is randomly transformed into another random rule on a random row of the grid. A vertical or horizontal alignment of the grid is chosen an a color set assigned. Sometimes, a simple 2d noise is applied to lighten (or well, darken) things a bit. The grid is finite and confined by the amount of cells in a row and amount of rows fitting the canvas given cell size.

The properties are recorded as features, more as a reference to the building blocks, rather then rarity indication. Probably be best viewed in live mode :)

Pressing 's' in live mode will save the png of the output.

metadata.name: Chocolate fold #89
metadata.description:
Marzipan chocolate is one of my favorite treat. 

The bar is wrapped with thin foil that can be fold so easily it could be turn into some kind of random algorithm.

Go to https://www.artgorithm.com/experiment-23-chocolate-fold/ (or https://twitter.com/artgorithme) for an example of Marzipan chocolate folds that inspired this work.

A new serie of folds appears after 10 secondes.


Press
- 'p' to download a png
